column49: I am writing to express my regret with your site discontinuing teacher access to buy technology items with bonus points. Without any prior warning the technology items such as Ipad , watches and computers are no longer available to teachers.  I have submitted many orders  over the past 15 years worth more than $1,000 dollars each year. I had been saving up points to purchase Ipads and then came to find out this fall these items have been discontinued.  I will not be submitting the same number of orders or putting the effort into submitting multiple orders a year because of Scholastic Book Clubs lack of regard for their teachers and giving prior notice so that we could use our point.   I know everyone at my school is very disappointed by Scholastic's decisions regarding these issues.

column38: Other, I was looking for winter book packs to give as gifts for my students before winter break.
column49: I was disappointed with your selection of winter book titles for 5th grade that came in a pack. I can not afford $5 a book for each of my 30 students in class. I would have loved to give them a winter themed book as a gift, but I will have to think of something else instead.    I also wish you wouold go back to the paper order forms for students to send in instead of the QR codes and digital fliers. Not one of my students have placed an order yet this year - and usually I have students spending $50 or more dollars a month on book orders. NONE of them are placing orders because it is entirely online and the famiies do NOT speak English. The kids will get the parents to send them with money for a book order - but they can not navigate a site in English and make a purchase with a credit card! I am soooooo disappointed in this new system! PLEASE bring back the paper order forms!

column49: I wish you would bring back some of the older stories, classic stories.    I ordered a few books for me, personally, to give to my grandkids.  Scholastic used to be a fun magazine to look through, because there were so many good books, but this seems to have changed.  Kids used to sit in my classroom and circle so many books they wanted.  This doesn't seem to be the case anymore.    In my opinion, I'm so tired of seeing The Good Egg stories.  They have a good theme, but they appear over and over.      Please return to some of the classics, fun stories.    Kids just need a good story.  A funny story.  Please make some changes.

column49: I  am VERY disappointed  in the new changes that were made to the site.  My understanding is the Scholastic's mission is to get books into the hands of ALL students. I am at a Title 1 school with the highest population of homelessness in our district, and the parents who want to order want to give me cash. Some of my parents are not literate and trying to navigate a website is difficult for them. Taking away the option for teachers to place a student order is a bad choice.  Also, having online orders send automatically is also not a good choice. My parents are not typically on time with things and I often have to wait for them before I place an order. I would prefer if my order went in all at the same time. That reduces the shipments and the books all come in one order.  When one student receives their order but the others did not yet because of the automatic ordering, they become upset. It would be nice to let the teachers choose what option they would like.

column49: I think that the changes you all have made this year have made it hard to support Scholastic. The prices for the products, as well as shipping have gone up. This has been the lowest participation in Book Orders that I have had in my 16 years as a teacher. Scholastic used to be a place to come for a good deal on books, but now it is not as much of a bargain. I also don't like how you set my order date. It makes it difficult, especially when holidays fall at the end of the month, so I either have to submit orders seperately and not get rewards, or the families risk not getting their items on time. This may be the last year that I use Scholastic, which is unfortunate because the kids always get so excited about new books, but the overall customer satisfaction and appeal to families has drastically gone down.

column49: I am very disappointed in Scholastic recently.  Since your push for all online and only the single flier for the holiday books, my classroom orders have dropped significantly.  I am the Scholastic teacher for my entire preschool.  I use our points to order every student a book at Christmas and at the end of the year.  I have been in charge of the school orders for over 10 years and have always earned enough points to pay for the children's.  This year my orders have gone from top tier rewards to bottom tier, the parents do not like the changes and are not ordering any longer.  At the rate I am earning points after this school year I will no longer be able to purchase books for the kids.  They are just too expensive now.  I am sad to say this may be our last year utilizing your company.

column49: I don't agree that families should have to submit orders online only - there needs to be an option for teachers to place orders for students. By taking away that option you are making it more difficult for the families/teachers to place orders. column49: As the director of a preschool I had some concerns about an article I read stating that, as a  school, we do not have the ability to opt out of the materials pertaining to gender and sexuatlity.  When I visited your site to verify this information I did see theses items were included on the diversity page.  We have both, children who English is there second language as well as those who have physical challenges, I do not think these topics, which are wonderful and great conversation starters in the classroom are the same as gender and sexuality, which are topics not proper for classroom  conversations.  I am will not promote Scholastic Books if that means I do not have the option to not promote material on gender and sexuality.  I strongly recommend  these items be on a seperate page and I as a director, have the option not to offer them through my school page.

column49: I taught 15 years ago, and Scholastic was amazing.  Great prices,  great selection, books didn't cost as much in bonus points. etc.  I've been home for 15 years raising my children, and now Scholastic is not so great - I always have difficultly doing something on this site. I can't believe that my eWallet from our Scholastic Book Fair money is now gone.  ($13)  I still had money and I was planning on spending it when I could sit down at home and because it was the next day, my eWallet no longer was there!! Even if  money will be there next year, there was no email explaining where the money went.  What do I tell my classroom parents who donated the money... oh by the way, I went home to order because there were slim pickins at the fair, but Scholastic made my money "disappear."  I think this is completely  shady and I am very disappointed. As for the book fair, I remember the Scholastic Book Fair being akin to Christmas morning - beautiful displays, tons of titles to choose from at the

column49: I'm not fond of the changes to the book orders. As a teacher for 25 years I have supported my students getting books from Scholastic. The points and bonus points makes a huge incentive for my students to purchase books because I give those points back to my students at the end of the year. Students are able to get free books for their summer reading. Unfortunately, the bonus points and incentives are lacking this year. In the past, my students have accumulated over 10,000 points by this time. However, that is not true this year because that bonus point has not been made available. It's very disappointing.     Also, the deals on books has also diminished. I'm searching for $1 or $2 books to purchase for my students as a gift for the holidays. I understand that pricing has increased due to inflation however with 33 students I'm unable to purchase them a book this year for a gift. I can't afford $3 - $5 for books for my students and I'm extremely disappointed.

column49: I have been teaching for 33 years and have enjoyed being a part of your book club. I usually give my students books at the beginning of the year,  Christmas and end of the year. There have years that I have bought them more.I  have enjoyed building my class library as well my home library(For my own children and now my grandchildren)  The last several years I struggled getting a books for my class at the beginning and now Christmas. You have priced your books out of my spending limit. Where are the dollar books? Where are the 10 for $10? Where do you go now when your amount is over $100 for the deals?? Why do teachers pay taxes on books and students do not? We are the ones directing them to your book club!! I tell them to buy them online because they are cheaper(Even during the Book Fairs at school).  I'm very disappointed! I know this means nothing to you, but it's sad that teachers are trying to encourage readers but can't get a break on putting them in their hands!

column49: As a teacher, I have to say I absolutely hate your new Book Club. I rarely even send home the flyers anymore. I miss Seesaw and the other clubs.  And I miss the bargain books terribly.  I used to order $1 books for my kids every month.  I can longer afford to do it. I know times are tough, inflation yada yada.  But you'd probably get more orders with a better price and make up the difference.  And I am not happy with how you changed book fairs and prevented certain themes from being a choice. How dare you, as a book club, prevent kids from all walks of life from reading books that could be about them and benefit them, help them, and potentially save them.  Books are a priceless lifeline.  Do better.

column49: I was looking for the scholastic bonus points catalog, when I saw that with the new website changes the bonus catalog is now just "shop with bonus points."  I went to look for some Apple products that I have been saving my bonus points up for, and I was vey surprised to see that ALL bigger ticket technology items have been removed from the options!  I know that my opinion really doesn't matter, but I am writing to express my discontent.  For over 16 years, I have been saving up to be able to get some nicer technology pieces for my classroom since our district does not provide technology of this quality.  I am disappointed that it is now all gone.  I am much less motivated in terms of continuing the book orders, as the Apple product bonus point options were a BIG motivator for me to use the company in my classroom.

column49: I used to love this site and doing the book orders in my classroom.  I hate it now.    I really really don't like having forced due dates.  My last batch of parent orders got processed before I was done with my order so I just didn't place a teacher order.  I hate the major increase in prices and the one book catalog like every 2 months.  I hate that you have more junk books and toys, etc. and less quality books.  I'm disappointed that you aren't doing the book of the week for $1 anymore since this was often how I was able to purchase books for some of my students that weren't able to purchase books.  I am going to try to keep going this year but the way it is going I will probably use up my bonus points by the end of the year and be done with it.  I have no incentive to purchase books from you if I can get books for the same price on Amazon.  I have always told other teachers that they should join but even I don't really want to be a member anymore.

column49: I am still very upset about not getting a warning that the club points bank prizes would be changing.  I had been saving my points for many years to get a wonderful gift for myself.  Now, all the items that I get with my points are items that I already have in  my classroom or ones that I do not need.  Gift cards are no longer a choice either--very disappointing.  This has upset many teachers at my school--so much that we are looking at different book clubs to use in the future instead of Scholastic.  It's the little things that make teachers happy/excited and to be able to get something we really want for "free" without having to spend our own money was something that many of us looked forward to.  At least keep the gift card option for teachers to get with their points.
